She flipped to a blank page and wrote down the date. Below that, she wrote "11.5.648–13.12.648".
"Are you digging up old memories?" Ivory asked, looking at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think she'll let you out for Christmas? There are only a few days left."
Kari knocked twice on the lantern. "No," as Ivory had suspected. The Ice King never let Kari out, as he considered her a "blemish". She was born deaf and was the only daughter in the family, all her siblings were boys.
Something similar applied to Ivory as well. When Ivory came out as non-binary, it seemed as if the world changed. As punishment for this difference, Ivory was given tasks that required spending most of the time alone.
Moreover, Ivory was also forced to serve the princess. However, it didn't bother Ivory much, as Ivory gained a friend.
"You're going to have your birthday soon, right?" Ivory asked, thinking about how the princess would have her birthday in a few days. Kari nodded with a sad flicker in her bright blue eyes.
"Would you like to celebrate your birthday?" Ivory asked, thinking about the last time the princess had answered this question.
"No," Kari tapped. Ivory knew this was a difficult topic for her. Her birthday was the day she was locked in this room and her mother was banished. Ivory had been a baby at the time, but remembered how upset the servants and the city's inhabitants had been. Ivory had heard that Eirwen was a popular queen. And that strangely enough, she could also predict things that would later come true.
"Well, what would you like to do?" Ivory asked. Kari looked excitedly at Ivory. She held a piece of paper in her hand. On it was written:
15 x 15 cm canvas
White, various shades of blue
Brushes in six different sizes
Easel
“Are you asking me to get these things for you?” Ivory asked the silent princess, whose braids swung back and forth from her vigorous tapping. “Yes?” Ivory chuckled softly. The usually reserved princess showed so much enthusiasm. It was the first time she had asked for something that had nothing to do with books and came from outside her room.
“Okay! See you later?” Ivory asked, stood up, and slung their way through the chaos of paper and notebooks.
Kari nodded, turned back to her notes, and wrapped herself in her blanket.
Ivory left the room, relieved that the princess had finally stepped out of her comfort zone and asked for things beyond her reach, like art supplies.
Ivory ran through the corridors again and tried to ignore the gossip of the maids.
“I heard that she is possessed by Queen Eirwen and that's why she keeps going into this room again and again.”
“I heard that she eats children in this room.”
“She looks like a man, that’s not normal, is it?”
Ivory covered her ears because she simply couldn't ignore the chatter and continued walking. The royal painter's room was located in the east wing, behind the second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was decorated as artfully as Karis' door. On it was the White Dragon, one of the six primordial dragons supposedly responsible for creating Frostfell. For a history-loving painter, the White Dragon on the door made perfect sense.
Ivory opened the door and expected the usual chaos. Paint splatters everywhere, brushes and paper scattered throughout the room, easels covering every centimeter of the wall. Unexpectedly, however, a different scene presented itself. The entire room was clean, and against a backdrop of red velvet stood a chair. On the chair sat Crown Prince Aquilo, who was being portraitured.
“Good morning, Ivory! Would you like to watch how your future king is being portraitured?” Aquilo asked, winking at Ivory.
“Excuse me, little prince,” said Ivory, largely ignoring him and gathering the things the silent princess wanted. “I’m only here to get the art supplies.”
“My little girl wants to go already?” asked Aquilo. “But I want you to stay!”
“I don’t,” said Ivory, finding the art supplies on the list and placing them in a box. “Besides, I’m not a girl.”
However, the prince had a different opinion. “Oh sweetie, that’s just a phase! As you get older, you’ll grow out of it!” he said vaguely.
“I have to go,” said Ivory, feeling uncomfortable with the prince’s response. At the same time, Ivory remembered all the ugly remarks he and others had made about Ivory’s gender identity in the past. I just want to get away from here.
"You're already leaving?" Suddenly, the prince appeared at the door and ignored the loud objections of the royal painter.
"That's not the behavior of a future king!" said Ivory.
"No one will find out. People won't believe you and the painter will keep quiet if his life is worth anything." He looked at the painter briefly and then leaned closer to Ivory. "What do you think about a date?" Ivory had been harassed in the past, but never by a prince and certainly not by the crown prince.
"Do you actually know what the word 'No' means?" Ivory spat out and pushed the crown prince away from them.
"No," answered Aquilo with a smile. Of course, the crown prince, who can have whatever he wants, doesn't know what the word "No" means.
Ivory rolled their eyes. "Why would you want to go out with someone like me? You must have about 100 admirers?"
"Actually, it's 50," he interrupted Ivory, still smiling. He tossed his hair back, which swirled around in the cold air.
"Now get it! Why me? I'm a danger to the palace." Ivory crossed their arms.
"You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen." Aquilo lifted Ivory's chin with his finger and forced Ivory to look at him.
